 <sec id="sec013" sec-type="conclusions" class="sec">
  <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Results and discussion</div>
  <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Survey results from post- to pre- 
   <span class="italic">World Climate</span> sessions show highly statistically significant gain in the constructs capturing climate change knowledge, affect, and intent to act (
   <a rid="pone.0202877.t005" ref-type="table" href="#pone.0202877.t005">Table 5</a>), even after Bonferroni correction. Participation in 
   <span class="italic">World Climate</span> was associated with a gain in knowledge about climate change, including 
   <span class="italic">Impacts</span> (Cohen’s 
   <span class="italic">d</span> effect size [ES] = 0.35; 
   <span class="italic">p</span> &lt; 1E-9), the human role in climate change (
   <span class="italic">Cause</span>, ES = 0.27; 
   <span class="italic">p</span> &lt; 1E-9), and CO
   <sub>2</sub> accumulation dynamics (
   <span class="italic">Stock-flow</span>, ES = 0.35; 
   <span class="italic">p</span> &lt; 1E-9). 
   <span class="italic">World Climate</span> was associated with highly statistically significant gains in affective responses to climate change, including 
   <span class="italic">Urgency</span> (ES = 0.38; 
   <span class="italic">p</span> &lt; 1E-9) and 
   <span class="italic">Hope</span> (ES = 0.20; 
   <span class="italic">p</span> &lt; 1E-9), as well as gains in participants’ intent to take action on climate change (ES = 0.28, 
   <span class="italic">p</span> &lt; 1E-9).
  </p>
